{"title_page": "Khichu", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox prepared food\n| name             = khichu or papdi no lot (Gujarati dish)\n| image            = papdi no lot.JPG\n| caption          = \n| alternate_name   = Papdi no lot\n| country          = [[India]]\n| region           = [[Gujarat]]\n| creator          = \n| course           = \n| type             = [[Snack food|Snack]]; as dough for [[papadi/rice papad]]\n| served           = \n| main_ingredient  = [[Rice flour]], Jeera [[Cumin]], Green Chili, Ajwain,  Sea Salt, Alkaline Salt known as Papad Khar \n| variations       = Sesame seeds, Fresh Coriander leaves, Green Garlic\n| calories         = \n| other            = \n}}\n[[File:Kheechu (Cooked Rice Flour) Gujarati Food.jpg|thumb|Khichu]]\n'''Khichu''' or '''Khichiyu''' or '''Papadi no Lot''' is a dough for making [[papad]] also known as Papadi in Central Gujarat. H\nHowever, owing to its taste it is also consumed as Snack (side dish). It is made from rice flour of choice like Krushna Kamod, however, some other flours are also used. The snack is prepared by cooking flour in water like porridge with [[cumin]] seeds, ajwain, green chili, salt and an alkaline salt known as Papad Khar (An alkaline salt with major components as [[sodium carbonate]] and [[sodium bicarbonate]])<ref>[http://ir.cftri.com/7301/ Chemical composition of Papad Khar]</ref> and then steaming the lump for achieving solid that can be flattened. It is often served with groundnut or sesame oil and chilli powder.<ref>[http://www.tarladalal.com/Rice-Khichu-%28-Gujarati-Recipe%29-582r Rice khichu recipe  on taraladalal.com]</ref> The name khichiyu or khichu may be derived from the ductile nature of the dough or from khichdi like structure.<ref>[http://www.grosse.is-a-geek.com/lunch/khichiya.html Meaning of khichiyu from grosse.is-a-geek.com]</ref> (Khinch in Indic languages means to pull.)\n\nPapad made from this dough are known as Papadi in Central Gujarat or Khichiya Papad in Northern India. Khichu is traditionally eaten during the winter season when such Papads are made because of several factors but it is eaten round the year these days.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Gujarati cuisine]]\n[[Category:Indian snack foods]]\n\n\n{{India-cuisine-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2019}}\n{{Infobox prepared food\n| name             = khichu (Gujarati dish)\n| image            = Khichu.JPG\n| caption          = \n| alternate_name   = \n| country          = [[India]]\n| region           = [[Gujarat]]\n| creator          = \n| course           = \n| type             = [[Snack food|Snack]]; as dough for [[papad]]\n| served           = \n| main_ingredient  = [[Rice flour]], [[Cumin]], Alkaline Salt known as Papad Khar \n| variations       = \n| calories         = \n| other            = \n}}\n[[File:Kheechu (Cooked Rice Flour) Gujarati Food.jpg|thumb|Khichu]]\n'''Khichu''' or '''Khichiyu''' is a dough for making [[papad]], however, owing to its taste it is also consumed as Farsan (snack/side dish). It is made from rice flour, however, a few other flours are also used. The snack is prepared by cooking flour in water like porridge with [[cumin]] seeds and an alkaline salt known as Papad Khar (An alkaline salt with major components as [[sodium carbonate]] and [[sodium bicarbonate]])<ref>[http://ir.cftri.com/7301/ Chemical composition of Papad Khar]</ref> and then steaming the lump. It is often served with oil and chilli powder.<ref>[http://www.tarladalal.com/Rice-Khichu-%28-Gujarati-Recipe%29-582r Rice khichu recipe  on taraladalal.com]</ref> The name khichiyu or khichu is derived from the ductile nature of the dough.<ref>[http://www.grosse.is-a-geek.com/lunch/khichiya.html Meaning of khichiyu from grosse.is-a-geek.com]</ref> (Khinch in Indic languages means to pull.)\n\nPapad made from this dough are known as Khichiya Papad. Khichu is traditionally eaten during the monsoon season.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Gujarati cuisine]]\n[[Category:Indian snack foods]]\n\n\n{{India-cuisine-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Uvnsrp", "label": "safe", "comment": "Most liked snack in central Gujarat  eaten while making papads as well as during festivals like navratri and fair", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Khichu"}
{"title_page": "Green Eyes (1977 film)", "text_new": "{{Infobox television\n| show_name            = Green Eyes\n| image                = \n| image_size           = \n| image_alt            = \n| caption              = \n| genre                = War<br>Drama\n| creator              = \n| based_on             = \n| writer               = [[Eugene Logan]] and [[David Seltzer]]\n| screenplay           = \n| story                = \n| director             = [[John Erman]]\n| starring             = [[Paul Winfield]]\n| narrated             = \n| theme_music_composer = [[Fred Karlin]]\n| country              = United States\n| language             = English\n| num_episodes         = \n| executive_producer   = [[Philip Capice]]<br>[[Lee Rich]]\n| producer             = [[John Erman]]<br>David Seltzer<br>Ben Cunningham (assistant producer)<br>[[Christopher Seitz]] (associate producer)\n| editor               = [[John W. Wheeler]]\n| cinematography       = [[Terry K. Meade]]\n| location             = [[Philippines]]\n| company              = [[Lorimar Productions]]\n| distributor          = [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]]\n| budget               = \n| network              = ABC\n| picture_format       = Color\n| audio_format         = [[Monaural|Mono]]\n| runtime              = 100 minutes\n| first_aired          = January 3, 1977\n| last_aired           = \n| preceded_by          = \n| followed_by          = \n| website              = \n}}\n'''''Green Eyes''''' is a 1977 American [[television film|made-for-television]] [[war film|war]] [[drama (film and television)|drama film]] directed by [[John Erman]] and written by Eugene Logan and [[David Seltzer]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Green Eyes|url=http://www.tcm.com/tcmdb/title/415887/Green-Eyes/|publisher=Turner Classic Movies|accessdate=27 June 2016}}</ref> It is a \"touching and moving story\"<ref name=\"Peabody\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.peabodyawards.com/stories/story/green-eyes-vietnam-revisited|title=Green Eyes: Vietnam revisited|website=www.peabodyawards.com|access-date=2016-06-17}}</ref> about an Vietnam veteran Lloyd Dubeck ([[Paul Winfield]]) who went through a soul searching journey.\n\nThe film was produced by [[Lorimar Productions]] and broadcast on [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Green Eyes|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0074590/|publisher=IMDB|accessdate=27 June 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe film won a [[Peabody Award]] and a [[Humanitas Prize]] in 1977.<ref name=\"Peabody\"/>\n\n== Plot ==\nLloyd Dubeck ([[Paul Winfield]]),  \"a Vietnam veteran wounded both physically and psychologically. Released from a VA hospital, walking with a cane, he can\u2019t find work and can\u2019t seem to fit in. Dubeck finds a renewed sense of purpose by returning to Saigon to search for a Vietnamese  woman he had loved and a child he fathered but never got to see. All he knows, thanks to a single letter from her, is that it\u2019s a boy with green eyes\".<ref name=\"Peabody\"/>\n\nDuring his journey, he met a boy named Trung ([https://www.imdb.com/name/nm0501283/?ref_=tt_cl_t5 Lemi]) who tricked him and stole all his money at their first encounter, but later accompanied him to find his ex lover Em Thug ([https://www.imdb.com/name/nm0705165/?ref_=tt_cl_t4 Victoria Racimo]). They also formed a friendship, which led to a bond they would never forget. Going through several orphanages in [[Ho Chi Minh City|Saigon]] and seeing thousands of Vietnam street children, Dubeck changed his view and idea about the world and felt sympathetic towards the children, even though they were not his son. This experience also caused him to befriend a women named Margeret Sheen ([[Rita Tushingham]])<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://ritatushingham.com/1970.htm|title=The Rita Tushingham Home Page - Credits & Photos 1970 - 1979|website=ritatushingham.com|access-date=2016-06-17}}</ref> who worked for an orphanage.\n\nEventually, after he found that his son with Em Thug was dead, and Em Thug already moved on and had a baby with another American pilot, he decided to go back to the U.S. alone. At the last moment, he realized whom he really regarded as his son \u2013 Trung \u2013 and took Trung back to the US with him.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n* {{IMDb title|0074590}}\n\n\n[[Category:1977 television films]]\n[[Category:1970s war drama films]]\n[[Category:American television films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American war drama films]]\n[[Category:Peabody Award-winning broadcasts]]\n[[Category:Films directed by John Erman]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox television\n| show_name            = Green Eyes\n| image                = \n| image_size           = \n| image_alt            = \n| caption              = \n| genre                = Drama<br>War\n| creator              = \n| based_on             = \n| writer               = [[Eugene Logan]] and [[David Seltzer]]\n| screenplay           = \n| story                = \n| director             = [[John Erman]]\n| starring             = [[Paul Winfield]]\n| narrated             = \n| theme_music_composer = [[Fred Karlin]]\n| country              = United States\n| language             = English\n| num_episodes         = \n| executive_producer   = [[Philip Capice]]<br>[[Lee Rich]]\n| producer             = [[John Erman]]<br>David Seltzer<br>Ben Cunningham (assistant producer)<br>[[Christopher Seitz]] (associate producer)\n| editor               = [[John W. Wheeler]]\n| cinematography       = [[Terry K. Meade]]\n| location             = [[Philippines]]\n| company              = [[Lorimar Productions]]\n| distributor          = [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]]\n| budget               = \n| network              = ABC\n| picture_format       = Color\n| audio_format         = [[Monaural|Mono]]\n| runtime              = 100 minutes\n| first_aired          = January 3, 1977\n| last_aired           = \n| preceded_by          = \n| followed_by          = \n| website              = \n}}\n'''''Green Eyes''''' is a 1977 American [[television film|made-for-television]] [[drama (film and television)|drama]] [[war film]] directed by [[John Erman]] and written by Eugene Logan and [[David Seltzer]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Green Eyes|url=http://www.tcm.com/tcmdb/title/415887/Green-Eyes/|publisher=Turner Classic Movies|accessdate=27 June 2016}}</ref> It is a \"touching and moving story\"<ref name=\"Peabody\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.peabodyawards.com/stories/story/green-eyes-vietnam-revisited|title=Green Eyes: Vietnam revisited|website=www.peabodyawards.com|access-date=2016-06-17}}</ref> about an Vietnam veteran Lloyd Dubeck ([[Paul Winfield]]) who went through a soul searching journey.\n\nThe film was produced by [[Lorimar Productions]] and broadcast on [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Green Eyes|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0074590/|publisher=IMDB|accessdate=27 June 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe film won a [[Peabody Award]] and a [[Humanitas Prize]] in 1977.<ref name=\"Peabody\"/>\n\n== Plot ==\nLloyd Dubeck ([[Paul Winfield]]),  \"a Vietnam veteran wounded both physically and psychologically. Released from a VA hospital, walking with a cane, he can\u2019t find work and can\u2019t seem to fit in. Dubeck finds a renewed sense of purpose by returning to Saigon to search for a Vietnamese  woman he had loved and a child he fathered but never got to see. All he knows, thanks to a single letter from her, is that it\u2019s a boy with green eyes\".<ref name=\"Peabody\"/>\n\nDuring his journey, he met a boy named Trung ([https://www.imdb.com/name/nm0501283/?ref_=tt_cl_t5 Lemi]) who tricked him and stole all his money at their first encounter, but later accompanied him to find his ex lover Em Thug ([https://www.imdb.com/name/nm0705165/?ref_=tt_cl_t4 Victoria Racimo]). They also formed a friendship, which led to a bond they would never forget. Going through several orphanages in [[Ho Chi Minh City|Saigon]] and seeing thousands of Vietnam street children, Dubeck changed his view and idea about the world and felt sympathetic towards the children, even though they were not his son. This experience also caused him to befriend a women named Margeret Sheen ([[Rita Tushingham]])<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://ritatushingham.com/1970.htm|title=The Rita Tushingham Home Page - Credits & Photos 1970 - 1979|website=ritatushingham.com|access-date=2016-06-17}}</ref> who worked for an orphanage.\n\nEventually, after he found that his son with Em Thug was dead, and Em Thug already moved on and had a baby with another American pilot, he decided to go back to the U.S. alone. At the last moment, he realized whom he really regarded as his son \u2013 Trung \u2013 and took Trung back to the US with him.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n* {{IMDb title|0074590}}\n\n\n[[Category:1977 television films]]\n[[Category:1970s war drama films]]\n[[Category:American television films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American war drama films]]\n[[Category:Peabody Award-winning broadcasts]]\n[[Category:Films directed by John Erman]]\n", "name_user": "Moe1810", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Green_Eyes_(1977_film)"}
{"title_page": "Wahhabi War", "text_new": "{{Infobox military conflict\n|conflict= Ottoman-Saudi War\n|image={{Location map many | Saudi Arabia\n| relief   = yes\n| width    = 300\n| caption  =\n\n| lat1_deg = 24.083333\n| lon1_deg = 38\n| pos1 = top\n| label1   = [[Battle of Yanbu|Yanbu]]\n\n| lat2_deg = 24.014715\n| lon2_deg = 39.051247\n| pos2 = bottom\n| label2   = [[Battle of Al-Safra|Al-Safra]]\n\n| lat3_deg = 24.466667\n| lon3_deg = 39.6\n| pos3 = right\n| label3   = [[Battle of Medina (1812)|Medina]]\n\n| lat4_deg = 21.543333\n| lon4_deg = 39.172778\n| pos4 = left\n| label4   = [[Battle of Jeddah (1813)|Jeddah]]\n\n| lat5_deg = 21.416667\n| lon5_deg = 39.816667\n| pos5 = bottom\n| label5   = [[Battle of Mecca (1813)|Mecca]]\n\n| lat6_deg = 24.7332576\n| lon6_deg = 46.5727909\n| label6   = [[Siege of Diriyah|Diriyah]]\n}}\n|caption=Sites of major battles during the war.\n|date=Early 1811 \u2013 1818\n|place=[[Arabian Peninsula]]\n|casus=Saudi conquest of [[Mecca]] since 1802 from the [[Ottoman Empire]].\n|result=Decisive Ottoman-Egyptian victory. <br />Destruction of the [[Emirate of Diriyah]] (First Saudi State) \n|combatant1={{flagdeco|Saudi Arabia|1744}} [[Emirate of Diriyah]] <br /> [[Al-Qasim]]\n|combatant2={{flagdeco|Ottoman Empire}} [[Ottoman Empire]] <br /> \n*[[File:Flag of Egypt (1793-1844).svg|border|22px]] [[Egypt Eyalet]]\n|commander1={{flagdeco|Saudi Arabia|1744}} [[Saud Ibn Abdul Aziz Ibn Mohammed Ibn Saud|Saud al-Kabeer]]{{KIA}}<br />{{flagdeco|Saudi Arabia|1744}} [[Abdullah bin Saud|Abdullah I]]{{Executed}}<br />{{flagdeco|Saudi Arabia|1744}} [[Ghassab bin Shar'an|Ghassab bin<br>Shar'an]]{{Executed}}<br / >{{flagdeco|Saudi Arabia|1744}} [[Sulayman ibn Abd Allah]]{{Executed}}<br / >{{flagdeco|Saudi Arabia|1744}} [[Ghaliyya al-Wahhabiyya]]{{KIA}}\n|commander2={{flagdeco|Ottoman Empire}} [[Mahmud II]] <br />   [[File:Flag of Egypt (1793-1844).svg|border|22px]] [[Tusun Pasha]]{{KIA}}<br />[[File:Flag of Egypt (1793-1844).svg|border|22px]] [[Muhammad Ali Pasha]]<br />[[File:Flag of Egypt (1793-1844).svg|border|22px]] [[Ibrahim Pasha of Egypt|Ibrahim Pasha]]<br />{{flagicon image|Flag of Egypt (1793-1844).svg}} [[Ahmed Bonaparte|Ahmed Bonaparte]] \n\n|strength1=20,000\n|strength2=50,000\n|casualties1=4,000 dead<br />6,000 wounded<ref name=\"Alexei Vasiliev\">{{cite book|last1=Vasiliev|first1=Alexei|title=The History of Saudi Arabia|publisher=NYU Press|isbn=9780814788097|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Dhh-PwAACAAJ&dq=The+History+of+Saudi+Arabia+Alexei+Mikhailovich+Vasiliev&hl=ar&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjf1qyRoqHSAhXDthQKHXgmAbMQ6AEIHTAA|accessdate=21 February 2017}}</ref>\n|casualties2=2,000 dead<br />1,000 wounded\n}}\n{{Campaignbox Ottoman\u2013Saudi War}}\n{{Campaignbox Muhammad Ali of Egypt}}\n\nThe '''Ottoman-Saudi War''' ({{lang-tr|Osmanl\u0131-Suudi Sava\u015flar\u0131}}, {{lang-ar|\u0627\u0644\u062d\u0631\u0628 \u0627\u0644\u0639\u062b\u0645\u0627\u0646\u064a\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u0633\u0639\u0648\u062f\u064a\u0629}}) was fought from early 1811 to 1818, between [[Egypt Eyalet]] under the reign of [[Muhammad Ali Pasha]] (nominally under [[Ottoman Empire|Ottoman]] rule) and the army of the [[Emirate of Diriyah]], the First Saudi State, resulting in the destruction of the latter.\n\n==Background==\nThe Muhammed ibn AbdulWahab movement is a reformist revivalist movement within [[Islam]] founded by [[Muhammad ibn Abd-al-Wahhab]] that would lead to creation of the Emirate of Diriyah as he and [[Muhammad bin Saud]] launched their campaign to reform Islam and (allegedly) consolidate power in Arabia from their power-base, and its eventual crushing by the Ottoman Empire's Egyptian [[khedive]] [[Muhammad Ali of Egypt]].\n\nIn 1802 [[Wahhabi sack of Karbala|12,000 Wahhabis sacked Karbala in Iraq]] killing up to 5,000 people and plundering the [[Imam Husayn Shrine]].<ref name=\"Bowen153\" /> By 1805, the Wahhabis controlled [[Mecca]] and [[Medina]].<ref name=\"Bowen153\" >{{cite book |last=Bowen |first=Wayne H. |title=The History of Saudi Arabia |year=2008 |publisher=Greenwood Press |location=Westport, CT |isbn=978-0313340123 |pages=153 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=S6J2Q3TlJpMC&pg=PA73&lpg=PA73&dq=1805+saudi+karbala&source=bl&ots=z7xkfvrX_x&sig=yg1NCeie86areM74Tp0N2ROwUf8&hl=en&ei=f4cCTbnlLsL38AaO_dTrAg&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=1&ved=0CBcQ6AEwAA#v=onepage&q=1805%20saudi%20karbala&f=false |oclc=166388162 }}</ref> The Armies also attacked Ottoman trade caravans which interrupted the Ottoman finances.<ref name=Marsot2007>[[Afaf Lutfi al-Sayyid-Marsot]]. ''A History of Egypt From the Islamic Conquest to the Present.'' New York: Cambridge UP, 2007.</ref> The Saudi [[Emir|amir]] denounced the Ottoman sultan and called into question the validity of his claim to be [[caliph]] and guardian of the sanctuaries of the [[Hejaz]]<ref name=Sirriyeh1989>Elizabeth Sirriyeh, Salafies, \"Unbelievers and the Problems of Exclusivism\".  ''Bulletin'' (British Society for Middle Eastern Studies), Vol. 16, No. 2. (1989), pp. 123-132.  ([https://www.jstor.org/stable/195146 Text online at JSTOR])</ref> and the Ottoman Empire, suspicious of the ambitious Muhammad Ali, instructed him to fight the Sauds armies, as the defeat of either would be beneficial to them.<ref name=\"Marsot2007\" /> Tensions between Muhammad Ali and his [[Albanians|Albanian]] troops also prompted him to send them to Arabia and fight against the Saudi armies where many died.<ref name=\"FahmyRuler30\">{{cite book|last=Fahmy|first=Khaled|title=Mehmed Ali: From Ottoman Governor to Ruler of Egypt|year=2012|publisher=Oneworld Publications|isbn=9781780742113|url=https://books.google.com.au/books?id=0pmcAwAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover&dq=Mehmed+Ali:+From+Ottoman+Governor+to+Ruler+of+Egypt&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjyr7awhtrXAhUHv5QKHXoYBNoQ6AEIJjAA#v=onepage&q=ongoing%20war&f=false|pages=30|ref=harv}}</ref>\n\n==Campaigns==\n[[Image:Image-Abdullah bin Saud FSS2.JPG|thumb|right|Painting of [[Abdullah bin Saud]], convicted and executed after losing the war.]]\nMuhammad Ali was ordered to crush the Saudi state as early as December 1807 by Sultan [[Mustafa IV]], however internal strife within Egypt prevented him from giving full attention to the this cause. The Albanians were not able to recapture the holy cities until 1811.<ref name=\"Sirriyeh1989\" />\n\nin 1817, [[Ibrahim Pasha of Egypt|Ibrahim Pasha]], Muhammad Ali's son, had taken over the campaign, gaining support of the volatile Arabian tribes by skillful diplomacy and lavish gifts, he advanced into central Arabia to occupy the towns of [[Unaizah]] and [[Buraidah]]. He was then joined by most of the principal tribes and marched to the Saudi capital [[Diriyah]]. However, their march to Diriyah was met with resistance by the emirates armies when they arrived in Diriyah in April 1818. It took until September for the armies to surrender, in part due to Ibrahim's poorly trained soldiers. Diriyah was destroyed in June 1819 and Egyptian [[garrison]]s were posted in the principal towns.\n\nIt was not until September 1818 that the first Saudi state ended with the surrendering of its leaders and the head of the Saudi state, [[Abdullah bin Saud]], who was sent to Istanbul to be executed.<ref name=\"Sirriyeh1989\" />\n\n==Aftermath==\nMost of the political leaders were treated well but the Ottomans were far harsher with the religious leaders that inspired the Wahhabi movement, executing [[Sulayman ibn Abd Allah]] and other religious notables, as they were thought to be uncompromising in their beliefs and therefore a much bigger threat than political leaders. The execution also reflects the Ottoman resentment of the Wahhabist views.<ref name=\"Sirriyeh1989\" />\n\nThis war had formed the basic hatred against the Wahhabi ideology among the Ottomans, and it continued to influence even modern Turkey when Turkish Islamic preachers consider Wahhabism to be non-Islam; virtually Turkish population is anti-Wahhabism. For the Saudis, who would form the nation a century later, the Saudis considered it as the first struggle for independence from the oppressive Ottoman Empire, and the current state of relationship between Saudi Arabia and Turkey is still influenced by this hostile past, whereas systematic campaign by the Saudis to rewrite the Ottoman past was denounced in Turkey.<ref>https://www.trtworld.com/opinion/turkophobia-is-behind-the-saudi-washing-of-ottoman-history-29545</ref><ref>https://ahvalnews.com/turkish-dramas/saudis-mbc-launching-new-drama-series-exposing-ottoman-tyranny</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Fitnat al-Wahhabiyya]]\n* [[Nejd Expedition]]\n* [[Hadith of Najd]]\n* [[Saudi Arabia\u2013Turkey relations]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ottoman-Saudi War}}\n[[Category:19th century in Saudi Arabia]]\n[[Category:Egypt under the Muhammad Ali dynasty]]\n[[Category:History of Nejd]]\n[[Category:Military campaigns involving the Ottoman Empire]]\n[[Category:Wars involving Saudi Arabia]]\n[[Category:Wars involving the Ottoman Empire]]\n[[Category:1810s in Egypt]]\n[[Category:Wahhabi War|*]]\n[[Category:1810s in Asia]]\n[[Category:Religion-based wars]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox military conflict\n|conflict= Ottoman-Saudi War\n|image={{Location map many | Saudi Arabia\n| relief   = yes\n| width    = 300\n| caption  =\n\n| lat1_deg = 24.083333\n| lon1_deg = 38\n| pos1 = top\n| label1   = [[Battle of Yanbu|Yanbu]]\n\n| lat2_deg = 24.014715\n| lon2_deg = 39.051247\n| pos2 = bottom\n| label2   = [[Battle of Al-Safra|Al-Safra]]\n\n| lat3_deg = 24.466667\n| lon3_deg = 39.6\n| pos3 = right\n| label3   = [[Battle of Medina (1812)|Medina]]\n\n| lat4_deg = 21.543333\n| lon4_deg = 39.172778\n| pos4 = left\n| label4   = [[Battle of Jeddah (1813)|Jeddah]]\n\n| lat5_deg = 21.416667\n| lon5_deg = 39.816667\n| pos5 = bottom\n| label5   = [[Battle of Mecca (1813)|Mecca]]\n\n| lat6_deg = 24.7332576\n| lon6_deg = 46.5727909\n| label6   = [[Siege of Diriyah|Diriyah]]\n}}\n|caption=Sites of major battles during the war.\n|date=Early 1811 \u2013 1818\n|place=[[Arabian Peninsula]]\n|casus=Saudi conquest of [[Mecca]] since 1802 from the [[Ottoman Empire]].\n|result=Decisive Ottoman-Egyptian victory. <br />Destruction of the [[Emirate of Diriyah]] (First Saudi State) \n|combatant1={{flagdeco|Saudi Arabia|1744}} [[Emirate of Diriyah]] <br /> [[Al-Qasim]]\n|combatant2={{flagdeco|Ottoman Empire}} [[Ottoman Empire]] <br /> \n*[[File:Flag of Egypt (1793-1844).svg|border|22px]] [[Egypt Eyalet]]\n|commander1={{flagdeco|Saudi Arabia|1744}} [[Saud Ibn Abdul Aziz Ibn Mohammed Ibn Saud|Saud al-Kabeer]]{{KIA}}<br />{{flagdeco|Saudi Arabia|1744}} [[Abdullah bin Saud|Abdullah I]]{{Executed}}<br />{{flagdeco|Saudi Arabia|1744}} [[Ghassab bin Shar'an|Ghassab bin<br>Shar'an]]{{Executed}}<br / >{{flagdeco|Saudi Arabia|1744}} [[Sulayman ibn Abd Allah]]{{Executed}}<br / >{{flagdeco|Saudi Arabia|1744}} [[Ghaliyya al-Wahhabiyya]]{{KIA}}\n|commander2={{flagdeco|Ottoman Empire}} [[Mahmud II]] <br />   [[File:Flag of Egypt (1793-1844).svg|border|22px]] [[Tusun Pasha]]{{KIA}}<br />[[File:Flag of Egypt (1793-1844).svg|border|22px]] [[Muhammad Ali Pasha]]<br />[[File:Flag of Egypt (1793-1844).svg|border|22px]] [[Ibrahim Pasha of Egypt|Ibrahim Pasha]]<br />{{flagicon image|Flag of Egypt (1793-1844).svg}} [[Ahmed Bonaparte|Ahmed Bonaparte]] \n\n|strength1=20,000\n|strength2=50,000\n|casualties1=4,000 dead<br />6,000 wounded<ref name=\"Alexei Vasiliev\">{{cite book|last1=Vasiliev|first1=Alexei|title=The History of Saudi Arabia|publisher=NYU Press|isbn=9780814788097|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Dhh-PwAACAAJ&dq=The+History+of+Saudi+Arabia+Alexei+Mikhailovich+Vasiliev&hl=ar&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjf1qyRoqHSAhXDthQKHXgmAbMQ6AEIHTAA|accessdate=21 February 2017}}</ref>\n|casualties2=2,000 dead<br />1,000 wounded\n}}\n{{Campaignbox Ottoman\u2013Saudi War}}\n{{Campaignbox Muhammad Ali of Egypt}}\n\nThe '''Wahhabi War'''  or '''Ottoman-Saudi War''' ({{lang-tr|Osmanl\u0131-Suudi Sava\u015flar\u0131}}, {{lang-ar|\u0627\u0644\u062d\u0631\u0628 \u0627\u0644\u0639\u062b\u0645\u0627\u0646\u064a\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u0633\u0639\u0648\u062f\u064a\u0629}}) was fought from early 1811 to 1818, between [[Egypt Eyalet]] under the reign of [[Muhammad Ali Pasha]] (nominally under [[Ottoman Empire|Ottoman]] rule) and the army of the [[Emirate of Diriyah]], the First Saudi State, resulting in the destruction of the latter.\n\n==Background==\nThe [[Wahhabism|Wahhabi]] movement is a reformist revivalist movement within [[Islam]] founded by [[Muhammad ibn Abd-al-Wahhab]] that would lead to creation of the Emirate of Diriyah as he and [[Muhammad bin Saud]] launched their campaign to reform Islam and consolidate power in Arabia from their power-base, and its eventual crushing by the Ottoman Empire's Egyptian [[khedive]] [[Muhammad Ali of Egypt]].\n\nIn 1802 [[Wahhabi sack of Karbala|12,000 Wahhabis sacked Karbala in Iraq]] killing up to 5,000 people and plundering the [[Imam Husayn Shrine]].<ref name=\"Bowen153\" /> By 1805, the Wahhabis controlled [[Mecca]] and [[Medina]].<ref name=\"Bowen153\" >{{cite book |last=Bowen |first=Wayne H. |title=The History of Saudi Arabia |year=2008 |publisher=Greenwood Press |location=Westport, CT |isbn=978-0313340123 |pages=153 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=S6J2Q3TlJpMC&pg=PA73&lpg=PA73&dq=1805+saudi+karbala&source=bl&ots=z7xkfvrX_x&sig=yg1NCeie86areM74Tp0N2ROwUf8&hl=en&ei=f4cCTbnlLsL38AaO_dTrAg&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=1&ved=0CBcQ6AEwAA#v=onepage&q=1805%20saudi%20karbala&f=false |oclc=166388162 }}</ref> The Wahhabis also attacked Ottoman trade caravans which interrupted the Ottoman finances.<ref name=Marsot2007>[[Afaf Lutfi al-Sayyid-Marsot]]. ''A History of Egypt From the Islamic Conquest to the Present.'' New York: Cambridge UP, 2007.</ref> The Saudi [[Emir|amir]] denounced the Ottoman sultan and called into question the validity of his claim to be [[caliph]] and guardian of the sanctuaries of the [[Hejaz]]<ref name=Sirriyeh1989>Elizabeth Sirriyeh, Salafies, \"Unbelievers and the Problems of Exclusivism\".  ''Bulletin'' (British Society for Middle Eastern Studies), Vol. 16, No. 2. (1989), pp. 123-132.  ([https://www.jstor.org/stable/195146 Text online at JSTOR])</ref> and the Ottoman Empire, suspicious of the ambitious Muhammad Ali, instructed him to fight the Wahhabis, as the defeat of either would be beneficial to them.<ref name=\"Marsot2007\" /> Tensions between Muhammad Ali and his [[Albanians|Albanian]] troops also prompted him to send them to Arabia and fight against the Wahhabi movement where many died.<ref name=\"FahmyRuler30\">{{cite book|last=Fahmy|first=Khaled|title=Mehmed Ali: From Ottoman Governor to Ruler of Egypt|year=2012|publisher=Oneworld Publications|isbn=9781780742113|url=https://books.google.com.au/books?id=0pmcAwAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover&dq=Mehmed+Ali:+From+Ottoman+Governor+to+Ruler+of+Egypt&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjyr7awhtrXAhUHv5QKHXoYBNoQ6AEIJjAA#v=onepage&q=ongoing%20war&f=false|pages=30|ref=harv}}</ref>\n\n==Campaigns==\n[[Image:Image-Abdullah bin Saud FSS2.JPG|thumb|right|Painting of [[Abdullah bin Saud]], convicted and executed after losing the war.]]\nMuhammad Ali was ordered to crush the Saudi state as early as December 1807 by Sultan [[Mustafa IV]], however internal strife within Egypt prevented him from giving full attention to the Wahhabis. The Albanians were not able to recapture the holy cities until 1811.<ref name=\"Sirriyeh1989\" />\n\nin 1817, [[Ibrahim Pasha of Egypt|Ibrahim Pasha]], Muhammad Ali's son, had taken over the campaign, gaining support of the volatile Arabian tribes by skillful diplomacy and lavish gifts, he advanced into central Arabia to occupy the towns of [[Unaizah]] and [[Buraidah]]. He was then joined by most of the principal tribes and marched to the Saudi capital [[Diriyah]]. However, their march to Diriyah was plagued by Wahhabi attacks when they arrived in Diriyah in April 1818. It took until September for the Wahhabis to surrender, in part due to Ibrahim's poorly trained army. Diriyah was destroyed in June 1819 and Egyptian [[garrison]]s were posted in the principal towns.\n\nIt was not until September 1818 that the Wahhabi state ended with the surrendering of its leaders and the head of the Wahhabi state, [[Abdullah bin Saud]], who was sent to Istanbul to be executed.<ref name=\"Sirriyeh1989\" />\n\n==Aftermath==\nMost of the political leaders were treated well but the Ottomans were far harsher with the religious leaders that inspired the Wahhabi movement, executing [[Sulayman ibn Abd Allah]] and other religious notables, as they were thought to be uncompromising in their beliefs and therefore a much bigger threat than political leaders. The execution also reflects the Ottoman resentment of the Wahhabist views.<ref name=\"Sirriyeh1989\" />\n\nThis war had formed the basic hatred against the Wahhabi ideology among the Ottomans, and it continued to influence even modern Turkey when Turkish Islamic preachers consider Wahhabism to be non-Islam; virtually Turkish population is anti-Wahhabism. For the Saudis, who would form the nation a century later, the Saudis considered it as the first struggle for independence from the oppressive Ottoman Empire, and the current state of relationship between Saudi Arabia and Turkey is still influenced by this hostile past, whereas systematic campaign by the Saudis to rewrite the Ottoman past was denounced in Turkey.<ref>https://www.trtworld.com/opinion/turkophobia-is-behind-the-saudi-washing-of-ottoman-history-29545</ref><ref>https://ahvalnews.com/turkish-dramas/saudis-mbc-launching-new-drama-series-exposing-ottoman-tyranny</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Fitnat al-Wahhabiyya]]\n* [[Nejd Expedition]]\n* [[Hadith of Najd]]\n* [[Saudi Arabia\u2013Turkey relations]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ottoman-Saudi War}}\n[[Category:19th century in Saudi Arabia]]\n[[Category:Egypt under the Muhammad Ali dynasty]]\n[[Category:History of Nejd]]\n[[Category:Military campaigns involving the Ottoman Empire]]\n[[Category:Wars involving Saudi Arabia]]\n[[Category:Wars involving the Ottoman Empire]]\n[[Category:1810s in Egypt]]\n[[Category:Wahhabi War|*]]\n[[Category:1810s in Asia]]\n[[Category:Religion-based wars]]\n", "name_user": "129.56.99.127", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eCampaigns)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wahhabi_War"}
{"title_page": "T24 (newspaper)", "text_new": "{{Infobox newspaper\n| name                 = T24\n| school               = \n| logo                 = \n| logo_size            = \n| logo_alt             = \n| image                = \n| image_size           = \n| image_alt            = \n| caption              = \n| motto                = Ba\u011f\u0131ms\u0131z \u0130nternet Gazetesi </br> (''Independent Internet Newspaper'')\n| type                 = [[online newspaper]]\n| format               = \n| owner                = Tempo24 Bas\u0131n Yay\u0131n Prod\u00fcksiyon Ltd. \u015eti.\n| founder              = <!-- or |founders= -->\n| publisher            = \n| president            = \n| editor               =\n| chiefeditor          = Do\u011fan Ak\u0131n (2009\u2013)<ref name=\"Founders (1)\"/>\n| depeditor            = \n| assoceditor          = \n| maneditor            = \n| generalmanager       = \n| newseditor           = \n| managingeditordesign = \n| dirinteractive       =\n| dirvisuals           =\n| dirvideo             =\n| campuseditor         = \n| campuschief          = \n| metroeditor          = \n| metrochief           = \n| opeditor             = \n| sportseditor         = \n| photoeditor          = \n| staff                = \n| foundation           = {{start date and age|2009|09|01}}\n| political            = [[Journalistic objectivity|Neutrality]]\n| language             = Turkish\n| ceased publication   = \n| relaunched           = \n| headquarters         = [[Istanbul]]\n| readership           = \n| sister newspapers    = \n| website              = https://t24.com.tr/\n| free                 = \n}}\n\n'''T24''' is a [[Turkey|Turkish]] [[online newspaper]]. \n\n==History==\nT24 was launched on 1 September 2009. Initial staff of T24 were consisting of former ''Tempo24'' employees.<ref name=\"Founders (1)\">{{cite news|first=|last=|authorlink=|author=|curly=|title=T24 internette yay\u0131na ba\u015flad\u0131|url=http://www.radikal.com.tr/hayat/t24-internette-yayina-basladi-952453/|format=|agency=|work=|publisher=[[Radikal]]|location=|id=|pages=|page=|date=1 September 2009|accessdate=21 April 2020|language=Tr|archiveurl=http://archive.is/mgOS1|archivedate=16 March 2016|quote=\"a\u011f\u0131ms\u0131z internet gazetesi T24; bug\u00fcn yay\u0131na ba\u015flad\u0131. Hi\u00e7bir kurum, \u00f6rg\u00fct ve ki\u015fiyle do\u011frudan ya da dolayl\u0131 bir ba\u011flant\u0131s\u0131 bulunmayan T24, k\u0131sa bir s\u00fcre yay\u0131nda kalmas\u0131na ra\u011fmen T\u00fcrkiye g\u00fcndemini etkileyen dosyalar yay\u0131mlayan Tempo24'\u00fc haz\u0131rlayan gazeteciler taraf\u0131ndan yay\u0131na sokuluyor.\"}}</ref>\n\nOn 29 December 2012, T24 started their [[Youtube]] channel and uploaded their first video on 12 April 2013. In 2013, author and columnist [[Hasan Cemal]] joined T24.<ref name=\"Hasan Cemal Hiring\">{{cite news|first=|last=|authorlink=|author=|curly=|title=Hasan Cemal kimdir? Nereli ve ka\u00e7 ya\u015f\u0131nda? \u0130\u015fte \u00fcnl\u00fc yazar hakk\u0131nda merak edilenler\u2026|url=https://www.sozcu.com.tr/2018/gundem/hasan-cemal-kimdir-nereli-ve-kac-yasinda-iste-unlu-yazar-hakkinda-merak-edilenler-2559623/|format=|agency=|work=|publisher=[[S\u00f6zc\u00fc]]|location=|id=|pages=|page=|date=6 August 2018|accessdate=21 April 2020|language=Tr|archiveurl=http://archive.is/wip/UM3ZT|archivedate=21 April 2020|quote=}}</ref> In June 2013, T24 columnist [[Alper G\u00f6rm\u00fc\u015f]], who formerly worked at [[Nokta]], [[Taraf]] and [[Yeni Akt\u00fcel]], accused the [[2013 Gezi Park protests|Gezi Park protestors]] as ''\"[[Coup d'\u00e9tat|pro-coup d'\u00e9tat]]\"''.<ref name=\"2013 Gezi Accusations\">{{cite news|first=|last=|authorlink=|author=|curly=|title=Alper G\u00f6rm\u00fc\u015f Gezi direni\u015f\u00e7ilerine \"darbeci\" dedi |url=https://odatv.com/alper-gormus-gezi-direniscilerine-darbeci-dedi-2506131200.html|format=|agency=|work=|publisher=[[OdaTV]]|location=|id=|pages=|page=|date=25 June 2016|accessdate=21 April 2020|language=Tr|archiveurl=http://archive.is/wip/xTG8Y|archivedate=21 April 2020|quote=\"T24 internet haber sitesinde yazan Alper G\u00f6rm\u00fc\u015f k\u00f6\u015fesinde Gezi eylemlerini konu ald\u0131. Gezi\u2019nin iki farkl\u0131 ruhu oldu\u011funu belirten G\u00f6rm\u00fc\u015f, Gezi eylemcilerinin darbeci oldu\u011funu da yazd\u0131. \u201cT\u00fcrkiye'yi sarsan 20 g\u00fcn ve onu izleyen \u2018d\u00fc\u015f\u00fck yo\u011funluklu direni\u015f\u2019in geride nas\u0131l bir tortu b\u0131rakaca\u011f\u0131 sorusunu, bence, bu 20 g\u00fcne damgas\u0131n\u0131 vuran iki sosyoloji temelinde cevapland\u0131rmal\u0131y\u0131z.\u201d diyen g\u00f6rm\u00fc\u015f, bu iki sosyolojiyi \u015f\u00f6yle a\u00e7\u0131klad\u0131: \u201cBu sosyolojilerden birincisini Gezi ruhunu temsil eden yeni nesil, ikincisini ise demokrasisiz bir laik diktat\u00f6rl\u00fck pe\u015finde ko\u015fan ulusalc\u0131l\u0131k olu\u015fturuyor.\u201d\"}}</ref>\n\nOn 14 January 2015, T24 published an entire instalment of [[Charlie Hebdo]], which included [[Muhammad the Prophet]] depicting  cartoons, following 2015 [[Charlie Hebdo shooting]].<ref name=\"Charlie Hebdo Cartoons\">{{cite news|first=|last=|authorlink=|author=|curly=|title=T24 Charlie Hebdo'nun son say\u0131s\u0131n\u0131n t\u00fcm\u00fcn\u00fc yay\u0131mlad\u0131|url=https://www.bbc.com/turkce/haberler/2015/01/150114_t24_charlie_hebdo|format=|agency=|work=|publisher=[[BBC Turkish]]|location=|id=|pages=|page=|date=|accessdate=21 April 2020|language=Tr|archiveurl=http://archive.is/wip/rKMXc|archivedate=21 April 2020|quote=}}</ref> In February 2015, T24 started their online [[Literary criticism|literay critism]] initiative '''Kitap K\u00fclt\u00fcr Kritik 24''' (K24).<ref name=\"K24 Kickoff\">{{cite news|first=|last=|authorlink=|author=|curly=|title=T24'\u00fcn online kitap kritik dergisi K24 yay\u0131na ba\u015fl\u0131yor\u2026|url=http://platform24.org/guncel/733/t24un-online-kitap-kritik-dergisi-k24-yayina-basliyor|format=|agency=|work=|publisher=platform24.org|location=|id=|pages=|page=|date=3 February 2015|accessdate=21 April 2020|language=Tr|archiveurl=|archivedate=21 April 2020|quote=}}</ref><ref name=\"K24 Nomination\">{{cite news|first=|last=|authorlink=|author=|curly=|title=K24, 2016 Bobs \u00d6d\u00fclleri finalinde...|url=https://www.t24.com.tr/haber/k24-2016-bobs-odulleri-finalinde,334477|format=|agency=|work=|publisher=[[T24 (newspaper)]]|location=|id=|pages=|page=|date=1 April 2016|accessdate=21 April 2020|language=Tr|archiveurl=http://archive.is/wip/wi6VL|archivedate=21 April 2020|quote=}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2016, columnist and literal critic [[Murat Belge]] joined T24.<ref name=\"Murat Belge Hiring\">{{cite news|first=|last=|authorlink=|author=|curly=|title=\nMurat Belge'nin yeni adresi neresi|url=https://odatv.com/murat-belgenin-yeni-adresi-neresi-1803161200.html|format=|agency=|work=|publisher=[[OdaTV]]|location=|id=|pages=|page=|date=18 March 2016|accessdate=21 April 2020|language=Tr|archiveurl=http://archive.is/wip/aOE55|archivedate=21 April 2020|quote=}}</ref>\n\nIn 23 October 2018, following the cancellation of her contract with [[CNN Turk]] co-administrator \u015eirin Payz\u0131n joined T24.<ref name=\"Sirin Payz\u0131n Hiring\">{{cite news|first=|last=|authorlink=|author=|curly=|title=\u015eirin Payz\u0131n T24'te|url=https://t24.com.tr/haber/sirin-payzin-t24te,730369|format=|agency=|work=|publisher=[[H\u00fcrriyet]]|location=|id=|pages=|page=|date=23 October 2018|accessdate=21 April 2020|language=Tr|archiveurl=http://archive.is/wip/2UVqn|archivedate=21 April 2020|quote=}}</ref>\n\nIn 2020, Do\u011fan Ak\u0131n, one of the founders of website and chief editor was was put on a trial due to allegation of \"Support to a Terrorist Organization without having affiliation\", as reporting the news based on tweets posted by [[Fuat Avni]], an anonymous [[Tweeter]] account, which caused number of detentions of alleged persons affiliated [[FET\u00d6]] (formerly referred as ''[[G\u00fclen Movement]]'' until colloquially known [[2013 corruption scandal in Turkey|17-25 December Operations]] taken place).<ref name=\"2020 FETO Trial\">{{cite news|first=|last=|authorlink=|author=|curly=|title=Fuat Avni tweetlerinden yarg\u0131lanan T24 Genel Yay\u0131n Y\u00f6netmeni Do\u011fan Ak\u0131n: Cemaat dosyalar\u0131n\u0131 bask\u0131lara ald\u0131rmadan yay\u0131mlad\u0131k|url=https://t24.com.tr/haber/t-24-genel-yayin-yonetmeni-dogan-akin-in-yargilandigi-dava-basladi,861858|format=|agency=|work=|publisher=[[T24 (newspaper)]]|location=|id=|pages=|page=|date=19 February 2020|accessdate=21 April 2020|language=Tr|archiveurl=http://archive.is/wip/FYna7|archivedate=18 April 2020|quote=}}</ref>\n\n==Controversies==\nAlthough there is no self-proclaimation, T24 is occasionally labelled as a [[Liberalism|liberalist]] media outlet.<ref name=\"Liberalism labelling\">{{cite news|first=|last=|authorlink=|author=[[Nihat Gen\u00e7|Gen\u00e7, Nihat]]]]|curly=|title=Soner Yal\u00e7\u0131n kimin kaval\u0131?|url=https://veryansintv.com/soner-yalcin-kimin-kavali/|format=|agency=|work=|publisher=veryansintv.com|location=|id=|pages=|page=|date=21 February 2020|accessdate=18 April 2020|language=Tr|archiveurl=http://archive.is/wip/0io10|archivedate=21 April 2020|quote=}}</ref>\n\nChief editor Do\u011fan Ak\u0131n, who is a former [[Do\u011fan Holding]] employee before joining T24, was accused by Zekeriya Say, columnist at [[Yeni Akit]] newspaper, for maintaining [[conflict of interest]] due to neutrality perilling relations with 3rd parties, alleged misuse of his connections in order to obtain [[funding]] for the newspaper.<ref name=\"COI Accusation\">{{cite news|first=|last=|authorlink=|author=|curly=|title=De\u011firmenin suyu nereden geliyor, T24?|url=https://www.yeniakit.com.tr/yazarlar/zekeriya-say/degirmenin-suyu-nereden-geliyor-t24-30077.html|format=|agency=|work=|publisher=[[Yeni Akit]]|location=|id=|pages=|page=|date=|accessdate=21 April 2020|language=Tr|archiveurl=http://archive.is/JL37D|archivedate=21 April 2020|quote=}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|3}}\n\n==External link==\n* [https://t24.com.tr/ Official Website]\n* [https://www.youtube.com/user/T24comtr T24] at [[Youtube]]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:T24 (newspaper)}}\n[[Category:Turkish-language newspapers]]\n[[Category:2009 establishments in Turkey]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox newspaper\n| name                 = T24\n| school               = \n| logo                 = \n| logo_size            = \n| logo_alt             = \n| image                = \n| image_size           = \n| image_alt            = \n| caption              = \n| motto                = Ba\u011f\u0131ms\u0131z \u0130nternet Gazetesi </br> (''Independent Internet Newspaper'')\n| type                 = [[online newspaper]]\n| format               = \n| owner                = Tempo24 Bas\u0131n Yay\u0131n Prod\u00fcksiyon Ltd. \u015eti.\n| founder              = <!-- or |founders= -->\n| publisher            = \n| president            = \n| editor               =\n| chiefeditor          = Do\u011fan Ak\u0131n (2009\u2013)<ref name=\"Founders (1)\"/>\n| depeditor            = \n| assoceditor          = \n| maneditor            = \n| generalmanager       = \n| newseditor           = \n| managingeditordesign = \n| dirinteractive       =\n| dirvisuals           =\n| dirvideo             =\n| campuseditor         = \n| campuschief          = \n| metroeditor          = \n| metrochief           = \n| opeditor             = \n| sportseditor         = \n| photoeditor          = \n| staff                = \n| foundation           = {{start date and age|2009|09|01}}\n| political            = [[Journalistic objectivity|Neutrality]]\n| language             = Turkish\n| ceased publication   = \n| relaunched           = \n| headquarters         = [[Istanbul]]\n| readership           = \n| sister newspapers    = \n| website              = https://t24.com.tr/\n| free                 = \n}}\n\n'''T24''' is a [[Turkey|Turkish]] [[online newspaper]]. \n\n==History==\nT24 was launched on 1 September 2009. Initial staff of T24 were consisting of former ''Tempo24'' employees.<ref name=\"Founders (1)\">{{cite news|first=|last=|authorlink=|author=|curly=|title=T24 internette yay\u0131na ba\u015flad\u0131|url=http://www.radikal.com.tr/hayat/t24-internette-yayina-basladi-952453/|format=|agency=|work=|publisher=[[Radikal]]|location=|id=|pages=|page=|date=1 September 2009|accessdate=21 April 2020|language=Tr|archiveurl=http://archive.is/mgOS1|archivedate=16 March 2016|quote=\"a\u011f\u0131ms\u0131z internet gazetesi T24; bug\u00fcn yay\u0131na ba\u015flad\u0131. Hi\u00e7bir kurum, \u00f6rg\u00fct ve ki\u015fiyle do\u011frudan ya da dolayl\u0131 bir ba\u011flant\u0131s\u0131 bulunmayan T24, k\u0131sa bir s\u00fcre yay\u0131nda kalmas\u0131na ra\u011fmen T\u00fcrkiye g\u00fcndemini etkileyen dosyalar yay\u0131mlayan Tempo24'\u00fc haz\u0131rlayan gazeteciler taraf\u0131ndan yay\u0131na sokuluyor.\"}}</ref>\n\nOn 29 December 2012, T24 started their [[Youtube]] channel and uploaded their first video on 12 April 2013. In 2013, author and columnist [[Hasan Cemal]] joined T24.<ref name=\"Hasan Cemal Hiring\">{{cite news|first=|last=|authorlink=|author=|curly=|title=Hasan Cemal kimdir? Nereli ve ka\u00e7 ya\u015f\u0131nda? \u0130\u015fte \u00fcnl\u00fc yazar hakk\u0131nda merak edilenler\u2026|url=https://www.sozcu.com.tr/2018/gundem/hasan-cemal-kimdir-nereli-ve-kac-yasinda-iste-unlu-yazar-hakkinda-merak-edilenler-2559623/|format=|agency=|work=|publisher=[[S\u00f6zc\u00fc]]|location=|id=|pages=|page=|date=6 August 2018|accessdate=21 April 2020|language=Tr|archiveurl=http://archive.is/wip/UM3ZT|archivedate=21 April 2020|quote=}}</ref> In June 2013, T24 columnist [[Alper G\u00f6rm\u00fc\u015f]], who formerly worked at [[Nokta]], [[Taraf]] and [[Yeni Akt\u00fcel]], accused the [[2013 Gezi Park protests|Gezi Park protestors]] as ''\"[[Coup d'\u00e9tat|pro-coup d'\u00e9tat]]\"''.<ref name=\"2013 Gezi Accusations\">{{cite news|first=|last=|authorlink=|author=|curly=|title=Alper G\u00f6rm\u00fc\u015f Gezi direni\u015f\u00e7ilerine \"darbeci\" dedi |url=https://odatv.com/alper-gormus-gezi-direniscilerine-darbeci-dedi-2506131200.html|format=|agency=|work=|publisher=[[OdaTV]]|location=|id=|pages=|page=|date=25 June 2016|accessdate=21 April 2020|language=Tr|archiveurl=http://archive.is/wip/xTG8Y|archivedate=21 April 2020|quote=\"T24 internet haber sitesinde yazan Alper G\u00f6rm\u00fc\u015f k\u00f6\u015fesinde Gezi eylemlerini konu ald\u0131. Gezi\u2019nin iki farkl\u0131 ruhu oldu\u011funu belirten G\u00f6rm\u00fc\u015f, Gezi eylemcilerinin darbeci oldu\u011funu da yazd\u0131. \u201cT\u00fcrkiye'yi sarsan 20 g\u00fcn ve onu izleyen \u2018d\u00fc\u015f\u00fck yo\u011funluklu direni\u015f\u2019in geride nas\u0131l bir tortu b\u0131rakaca\u011f\u0131 sorusunu, bence, bu 20 g\u00fcne damgas\u0131n\u0131 vuran iki sosyoloji temelinde cevapland\u0131rmal\u0131y\u0131z.\u201d diyen g\u00f6rm\u00fc\u015f, bu iki sosyolojiyi \u015f\u00f6yle a\u00e7\u0131klad\u0131: \u201cBu sosyolojilerden birincisini Gezi ruhunu temsil eden yeni nesil, ikincisini ise demokrasisiz bir laik diktat\u00f6rl\u00fck pe\u015finde ko\u015fan ulusalc\u0131l\u0131k olu\u015fturuyor.\u201d\"}}</ref>\n\nOn 14 January 2015, T24 published an entire instalment of [[Charlie Hebdo]], which included [[Muhammad the Prophet]] depicting  cartoons, following 2015 [[Charlie Hebdo shooting]].<ref name=\"Charlie Hebdo Cartoons\">{{cite news|first=|last=|authorlink=|author=|curly=|title=T24 Charlie Hebdo'nun son say\u0131s\u0131n\u0131n t\u00fcm\u00fcn\u00fc yay\u0131mlad\u0131|url=https://www.bbc.com/turkce/haberler/2015/01/150114_t24_charlie_hebdo|format=|agency=|work=|publisher=[[BBC Turkish]]|location=|id=|pages=|page=|date=|accessdate=21 April 2020|language=Tr|archiveurl=http://archive.is/wip/rKMXc|archivedate=21 April 2020|quote=}}</ref> In February 2015, T24 started their online [[Literary criticism|literay critism]] initiative '''Kitap K\u00fclt\u00fcr Kritik 24''' (K24).<ref name=\"K24 Kickoff\">{{cite news|first=|last=|authorlink=|author=|curly=|title=T24'\u00fcn online kitap kritik dergisi K24 yay\u0131na ba\u015fl\u0131yor\u2026|url=http://platform24.org/guncel/733/t24un-online-kitap-kritik-dergisi-k24-yayina-basliyor|format=|agency=|work=|publisher=platform24.org|location=|id=|pages=|page=|date=3 February 2015|accessdate=21 April 2020|language=Tr|archiveurl=|archivedate=21 April 2020|quote=}}</ref><ref name=\"K24 Nomination\">{{cite news|first=|last=|authorlink=|author=|curly=|title=K24, 2016 Bobs \u00d6d\u00fclleri finalinde...|url=https://www.t24.com.tr/haber/k24-2016-bobs-odulleri-finalinde,334477|format=|agency=|work=|publisher=[[T24 (newspaper)]]|location=|id=|pages=|page=|date=1 April 2016|accessdate=21 April 2020|language=Tr|archiveurl=http://archive.is/wip/wi6VL|archivedate=21 April 2020|quote=}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2016, columnist and literal critic [[Murat Belge]] joined T24.<ref name=\"Murat Belge Hiring\">{{cite news|first=|last=|authorlink=|author=|curly=|title=\nMurat Belge'nin yeni adresi neresi|url=https://odatv.com/murat-belgenin-yeni-adresi-neresi-1803161200.html|format=|agency=|work=|publisher=[[OdaTV]]|location=|id=|pages=|page=|date=18 March 2016|accessdate=21 April 2020|language=Tr|archiveurl=http://archive.is/wip/aOE55|archivedate=21 April 2020|quote=}}</ref>\n\nIn 23 October 2018, following the cancellation of her contract with [[CNN Turk]] co-administrator \u015eirin Payz\u0131n joined T24.<ref name=\"Sirin Payz\u0131n Hiring\">{{cite news|first=|last=|authorlink=|author=|curly=|title=\u015eirin Payz\u0131n T24'te|url=https://t24.com.tr/haber/sirin-payzin-t24te,730369|format=|agency=|work=|publisher=[[H\u00fcrriyet]]|location=|id=|pages=|page=|date=23 October 2018|accessdate=21 April 2020|language=Tr|archiveurl=http://archive.is/wip/2UVqn|archivedate=21 April 2020|quote=}}</ref>\n\nIn 2020, Do\u011fan Ak\u0131n, one of the founders of website and chief editor was was put on a trial due to allegation of \"Support to a Terrorist Organization without having affiliation\", as reporting the news based on tweets posted by [[Fuat Avni]], an anonymous [[Tweeter]] account, which caused number of detentions of alleged persons affiliated [[FET\u00d6]] (formerly refered as ''[[G\u00fclen Movement]]'' until colloquially known [[2013 corruption scandal in Turkey|17-25 December Operations]] taken place).<ref name=\"2020 FETO Trial\">{{cite news|first=|last=|authorlink=|author=|curly=|title=Fuat Avni tweetlerinden yarg\u0131lanan T24 Genel Yay\u0131n Y\u00f6netmeni Do\u011fan Ak\u0131n: Cemaat dosyalar\u0131n\u0131 bask\u0131lara ald\u0131rmadan yay\u0131mlad\u0131k|url=https://t24.com.tr/haber/t-24-genel-yayin-yonetmeni-dogan-akin-in-yargilandigi-dava-basladi,861858|format=|agency=|work=|publisher=[[T24 (newspaper)]]|location=|id=|pages=|page=|date=19 February 2020|accessdate=21 April 2020|language=Tr|archiveurl=http://archive.is/wip/FYna7|archivedate=18 April 2020|quote=}}</ref>\n\n==Controversies==\nAlthough there is no self-proclaimation, T24 is occasionally labelled as a [[Liberalism|liberalist]] media outlet.<ref name=\"Liberalism labelling\">{{cite news|first=|last=|authorlink=|author=[[Nihat Gen\u00e7|Gen\u00e7, Nihat]]]]|curly=|title=Soner Yal\u00e7\u0131n kimin kaval\u0131?|url=https://veryansintv.com/soner-yalcin-kimin-kavali/|format=|agency=|work=|publisher=veryansintv.com|location=|id=|pages=|page=|date=21 February 2020|accessdate=18 April 2020|language=Tr|archiveurl=http://archive.is/wip/0io10|archivedate=21 April 2020|quote=}}</ref>\n\nChief editor Do\u011fan Ak\u0131n, who is a former [[Do\u011fan Holding]] employee before joining T24, was accused by Zekeriya Say, columnist at [[Yeni Akit]] newspaper, for maintaining [[conflict of interest]] due to neutrality perilling relations with 3rd parties, alleged misuse of his connections in order to obtain [[funding]] for the newspaper.<ref name=\"COI Accusation\">{{cite news|first=|last=|authorlink=|author=|curly=|title=De\u011firmenin suyu nereden geliyor, T24?|url=https://www.yeniakit.com.tr/yazarlar/zekeriya-say/degirmenin-suyu-nereden-geliyor-t24-30077.html|format=|agency=|work=|publisher=[[Yeni Akit]]|location=|id=|pages=|page=|date=|accessdate=21 April 2020|language=Tr|archiveurl=http://archive.is/JL37D|archivedate=21 April 2020|quote=}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|3}}\n\n==External link==\n* [https://t24.com.tr/ Official Website]\n* [https://www.youtube.com/user/T24comtr T24] at [[Youtube]]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:T24 (newspaper)}}\n[[Category:Turkish-language newspapers]]\n[[Category:2009 establishments in Turkey]]\n", "name_user": "Arjayay", "label": "safe", "comment": "refered > referred", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/T24_(newspaper)"}
{"title_page": "National Arts Festival", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date=July 2016}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2016}}\n{{Infobox recurring event\n |name = National Arts Festival\n |logo          = [[File:Grahamstown national arts festival.jpg|150px]]\n |image         =\n |caption       = Grahamstown Festival\n |location      = Makhanda (formerly Grahamstown)\n |years_active  = 45\n |founded       = 13 July 1973\n |dates         = June/July annually\n |genre         = Arts Festival\n |attendance    = 209 677 <ref name=\"rnews.co.za\">{{Cite web | title = National Arts Festival reports positive results for 2018 Festival | date = 2 August 2018 | accessdate = 9 May 2019 | url = https://www.rnews.co.za/article/21156/national-arts-festival-reports-positive-results-for-2018-festival | language =   | quote =  }}</ref>\n |patron        = [[Standard Bank]], [[M-Net|MNET]], National Lotteries Commission, City Press, Department of Arts and Culture, Eastern Cape Government\n |website       = [http://www.nationalartsfestival.co.za/ National Arts Festival]\n}}\n'''The National Arts Festival (NAF)''' is an annual festival of performing arts in [[Makhanda, Eastern Cape|Makhanda]] (formerly Grahamstown), [[South Africa]]. It is the largest arts festival on the African continent<ref>{{cite web|title=Grahamstown Festival \u2013 MSN Encarta <!-- BOT GENERATED TITLE -->|url=http://uk.encarta.msn.com/encyclopedia_781561394/grahamstown_festival.html|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20050824050000/http://uk.encarta.msn.com/encyclopedia_781561394/Grahamstown_Festival.html|archivedate=24 August 2005|url-status=dead|access-date=26 September 2009}}</ref> and one of the largest performing arts festivals in the world by visitor numbers.<ref>{{cite web|title=World Fringe Alliance|url=http://www.worldfringealliance.com/|accessdate=15 June 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe festival runs for 11 days, from the last week of June to the first week of July every year. It takes place in the small [[Rhodes University|university]] city of Makhanda (formerly Grahamstown),<ref name=\"maha_Grah\">{{Cite web\n| title = A Festival of Resistance\n| author = Ben Fogel\n| work = Mahala\n| date = 13 July 2012\n| accessdate = 6 September 2014\n| url = http://www.mahala.co.za/art/a-festival-of-resistance/\n| quote =\n}}</ref> in the [[Eastern Cape]] province of South Africa.\n\nThe NAF comprises a Main programme and a Fringe festival, both administered by the National Arts Festival Office, a [[nonprofit organization|non-profit]] Section 21 Company. The Festival programme includes [[performing arts]] (theatre, dance, stand-up comedy and live music), visual art exhibitions, films, talks and workshops, a large food and craft fair and historical tours of the city. The NAF runs a children's arts festival over the same period and a number of other festivals take place in Grahamstown over the period of the NAF, such as the [[National Youth Jazz Festival]].\n\nPerformances take place across the city in approximately 60 venues (such as theatres, churches, schools) as well as in various outdoor locations for the street performances.\n\nThe Festival attracts significant numbers of local and international visitors and is one of the biggest contributors to the economy of the region.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Antrobus|first1=Geoff|title=National Arts Festival Drives the Economy of Grahamstown|url=https://www.mediaupdate.co.za/media/59162/the-national-arts-festival-drives-the-economy-of-grahamstown-eastern-cape|website=Media Update|accessdate=15 June 2017}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\n\nMakhanda has been associated with carnivals and festivals for more than 180 years as British immigrants established the tradition of celebrating landmark anniversaries on a grand scale. When a movement gained ground last century to erect a memorial to these pioneers it was agreed that it should be a \"living\" monument presenting festivals, conferences and other gatherings.\n\nAn Inaugural Festival was held in 1974 when the [[1820 Settlers National Monument]] was officially opened, with the exception of 1975, a festival has been organised every year since then.\n\n== The main programme ==\n\nA committee of curators in the various disciplines selects the content of the main programme. The planning process takes into account what is available locally and from outside South Africa. Three considerations that influence decisions are the artistic merits of any submission, the creation of a varied and balanced programme, and the costs involved. The Committee strives for excellence in all aspects of the programme, an approach that has assisted in bringing in sponsorship money for world class shows from a number of foreign governments and large multinational corporations.\n\n== The fringe ==\n\nToday, the Fringe is on an equal footing with the Main Festival. Seasoned performers and famous directors can just as easily be found on either programme, and a slot on the main programme one year does not preclude a return to the Fringe the next. The distinguishing feature of the Fringe is that it is open to all and exempt from the selection process that applies to the main programme. Fringe participants are responsible for their own costs and 85% of their box office sales accrue to them directly. They are liable for certain payments for venue hire and registration fees.\n\n=== Subsidiary festivals ===\n\nA number of subsidiary festivals take place as part of the National Arts Festival:\n* Think Fest<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://thinkfest.wordpress.com/|title=Think!Fest|website=Think!Fest|access-date=2018-10-26}}</ref>\n* Spiritfest<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.grahamstowncathedral.org/spiritfest/|title=Spiritfest \u2013 Cathedral of St Michael and St George|website=www.grahamstowncathedral.org|access-date=2018-10-26}}</ref>\n* Wordfest<ref>{{Cite web | url=http://www.ru.ac.za/wordfest/ |title = Rhodes University-Where Leaders Learn}}</ref>\n* [[National Youth Jazz Festival]]\n* [[Fingo Festival]]\n* Creativate Digital Arts Festival\n* National Schools Festival\n\n== Young Artist Awards ==\n\nThe Young Artist Awards, sponsored by Standard Bank, are presented by the National Arts Festival Artistic Committee to emerging, relatively young South African artists who have demonstrated exceptional ability in their chosen fields but who have not yet achieved national exposure and acclaim.\n\nFestival Committee members, fellow artists and interested members of the public, nominate artists. The NAF Committee, a group of experts in the various arts disciplines, decides on the final recipients.\n\nDesigned to encourage the recipients in the pursuit of their careers, a key aspect of the awards is that they guarantee the artists a place on the main programme of the forthcoming National Arts Festival. Apart from a cash prize, each of the winners receive substantial financial backing for their Festival participation whether this involves the mounting of an exhibition or the staging of a production.\n\nA maximum of five awards are made annually in any one of the disciplines of drama, music, jazz, visual art, dance and film. Since the inception of the awards in 1981 more than 150 awards have been presented plus five special awards to artists in recognition of their contribution to the National Arts Festival and the arts of South Africa. A complete list of previous winners is as follows:<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.nationalartsfestival.co.za/about/young-artists/young-artists-award-history/ |title=Young Artist Award History |access-date=28 October 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141029040308/https://www.nationalartsfestival.co.za/about/young-artists/young-artists-award-history/ |archive-date=29 October 2014 |url-status=bot: unknown }}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year || Music !! Drama !! Dance !! Jazz !! Visual Art !! Other\n|-\n| 2020<ref>{{Cite web | url=http://www.artsvark.co.za/the-5-artists-changing-the-face-of-the-creative-industry/ | title=The 5 artists 